<div class="wp-forum-connect-container">

    
<div class="wp-forum-connect-featured">

    <h2 class="comments-title">Promoted Comments</h2>

    <div class="wp-forum-connect-comment-list">

                <article class="wp-forum-connect-comment">

            <div class="wp-forum-connect-comment-avatar">

                <img alt="" src="https://arstechnica.com/wp-content/plugins/article-forum-connect/public/img/avatar.png" srcset="https://arstechnica.com/wp-content/plugins/article-forum-connect/public/img/avatar.png 2x" class="avatar avatar-60 photo" height="60" width="60" loading="lazy">

            </div>

            <div class="wp-forum-connect-comment-message">

                <div>

                    <b class="fn"><a href="https://arstechnica.com/civis/members/excelleron.854706/" target="_blank">excelleron</a></b>

                </div>

                <div>

                    <blockquote class="xfBb-quote" data-name="tuna74">This is so wrong on so many levels. First, you don't get rid of motion blur, that is already encoded into the original source. And WTH does &quot;softer movements&quot; mean? I any case, motions should be more blurred and &quot;smother&quot; due to the interpolation of frames.</blockquote>I'll bite. I'm a DP by trade. Softer moments is certainly a phrase I would ascribe to 24p motion, shot with a 180 degree shutter. &quot;Blurry&quot; and &quot;smooth&quot; are not interchangeable here. That is actually the whole difference and we call it motion cadence. The drag of the shutter, the specific timing on pans, tilts, and other camera movement is all very considered. Motion interpolation in any form is making up frames. We specifically didn't want those frames there. We chose as professionals not to have them. Don't mess with my stuff.<br />
<blockquote class="xfBb-quote" data-name="tuna74">Also, soap operas are shot on 24 fps, the things that give them their specific look is their limited lighting, set design and make up (which is the same for sit comes filmed in front of an audience like Friends and similar).</blockquote>Soap operas are not shot at 24fps. And sitcoms in front of a live audience (which died in the early 2000's) were certainly not shot at 60fps, as they used film cameras. And the whole reason 24fps is a standard is because it is the lowest frame rate you can shoot and sound sync still works for a viewer (edit to add: this is called fluidity of motion). Film is expensive. They didn't want to roll any more than they had to. Viewers got accustomed to that frame rate for movies and it stuck. See the response to the HFR Hobbit movies. It doesn't look &quot;right&quot; for a movie.<br />
<br />
So, sorry. This is just utterly false information.
                </div>

                <div>

                    <a href="https://arstechnica.com/civis/posts/42908708/" target="_blank">

                        <time datetime="2024-06-12T23:28:42+00:00">June 12, 2024 at 11:28 pm</time>

                    </a>

                </div>

